CPU: 8 MHz 68000
VDP: custom Video/Audio/DMA chip

Games typically use double-buffered 320x240 at 8bpp.

64K-128K VRAM + 128K main RAM:
320 x 200 x 4-bit = 32000 x 2 = 64000    (32000 * 30 = ~1 MHz fill; ~2 MHz dual-cycle copy DMA)
320 x 200 x 8-bit = 64000 x 2 = 128000   (64000 * 30 = ~2 MHz fill; ~4 MHz dual-cycle copy DMA)
640 x 200 x 4-bit = 64000
640 x 200 x 8-bit = 128000
640 x 400 x 4-bit = 128000
640 x 400 x 8-bit = 256000 (expansion +128K VRAM)
800 x 600 x 4-bit = 240000 (expansion +128K VRAM)

Games - 320 x 200 x 4-bit x 2 = 64K VRAM + 192K main RAM
Desktop - 640 x 200 x 4-bit = 64K VRAM + 192K main RAM
Expansion - adds another 256K main RAM (512K total)

The DMA can perform:
• solid color fill
• scaled bitmap/pattern fill (transparent or opaque)
• scaled tilemap copy (indirect 8x8, 16x8, 16x16, 32x16 tilemap copy)
• source 1/2/4/8 bpp (palette base | pixel)

This is sufficient for SNES/Amiga-level multilayer graphics, except Mode 7.

